    { id: 287, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is a go-to-market strategy?", o: ["Financial accounting method", "Plan for distributing and promoting the product to reach target customers effectively at launch", "Manufacturing plan", "HR recruitment strategy"], a: 1, e: "A Go-to-Market Strategy defines how the product will be distributed, positioned, and promoted to reach target customers effectively at launch." },
    { id: 288, t: "Product Dev", q: "What does technical feasibility assessment evaluate?", o: ["User preferences", "Market size", "Whether the proposed product can realistically be built with available technology and resources", "Competitive landscape"], a: 2, e: "Technical Feasibility assesses whether a product can realistically be built — evaluating technological requirements and implementation challenges." },
    { id: 289, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is a sprint in Agile product development?", o: ["A long development cycle", "A fixed short time period typically 1-4 weeks during which a team completes a set of planned work items", "Running fast in a race", "An emergency fix"], a: 1, e: "A Sprint is a fixed time-box in Agile/Scrum development where a team commits to completing a defined set of work — enabling iterative delivery." },
    { id: 290, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is A/B testing in product development?", o: ["Two types of regression", "Two versions of source code", "Comparing two versions of a product feature to determine which performs better with users", "Two types of machine learning"], a: 2, e: "A/B Testing compares two versions of a product feature with different user groups — using data to determine which version achieves better outcomes." },
    { id: 291, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is competitive analysis in market research?", o: ["Ignoring the competition", "Hiring competitors' employees", "Copying competitors' products", "Analysing competitors' products, strengths, weaknesses and market positioning to inform product strategy"], a: 3, e: "Competitive Analysis examines competitors' products, strengths, weaknesses, and positioning — helping identify differentiation opportunities and strategic gaps." },
    { id: 292, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is scope creep in product development?", o: ["Reducing project scope over time", "Uncontrolled expansion of project scope beyond original objectives without corresponding resource adjustments", "Improving project scope clarity", "Reducing the number of features"], a: 1, e: "Scope Creep is the uncontrolled growth of a project's scope beyond original objectives — often causing delays, budget overruns, and quality issues." },
    { id: 293, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is a retrospective in Agile product development?", o: ["A financial review meeting", "Looking at historical sales data", "A user feedback session", "A regular team meeting to reflect on the past sprint — celebrating successes, identifying problems and agreeing on improvements"], a: 3, e: "A Retrospective is a structured reflection meeting after each sprint — the team identifies what went well, what didn't, and commits to specific improvements." },
    { id: 294, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is a product backlog in Agile development?", o: ["A prioritized list of all work items (features, bugs, improvements) to be done — the single source of truth for what the team will build", "Technical debt listing", "A financial budget report", "A list of completed features"], a: 0, e: "A Product Backlog is a prioritized list of all features, enhancements, and fixes to be built — managed by the Product Owner and continuously refined." },
    { id: 295, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is Kanban as a product development methodology?", o: ["A Japanese food dish", "A programming language", "A testing framework", "A visual workflow management system using cards and boards to track work items through production stages"], a: 3, e: "Kanban is a visual workflow management method using boards and cards to track tasks through stages — enabling teams to limit work-in-progress and improve flow." },
    { id: 296, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is design thinking in product development?", o: ["Technical specifications first", "User-centric problem solving through empathy, ideation, prototyping and testing", "Feature maximization", "Cost reduction only"], a: 1, e: "Design Thinking emphasizes deeply understanding user needs (empathy), generating creative solutions (ideation), and rapidly testing them (prototyping)." },
    { id: 297, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is a North Star Metric in product development?", o: ["The most complex KPI", "A single key metric that best captures the core value a product delivers to customers — guiding all product decisions", "A navigation tool", "The highest possible accuracy metric"], a: 1, e: "A North Star Metric is the single most important metric reflecting the product's core value delivery to customers — aligning the entire team's priorities." },
    { id: 298, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is churn rate in product analytics?", o: ["The percentage of customers who stop using the product over a given time period", "The rate of new feature releases", "The rate at which new users sign up", "The speed of data processing"], a: 0, e: "Churn Rate is the percentage of customers who discontinue using the product in a given period — a key metric for understanding product retention." },
    { id: 299, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is retention rate in product analytics?", o: ["The percentage of users who continue using the product over a given period — a key indicator of product-market fit and value", "Rate of retaining employees", "Data retention in databases", "Customer acquisition rate"], a: 0, e: "Retention Rate measures the percentage of users who continue using the product after their initial adoption — a crucial indicator of long-term value." },
    { id: 300, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is hypothesis-driven development in product management?", o: ["Framing product decisions as testable hypotheses and using experiments to validate or invalidate them with real data", "Developing based on gut feeling", "Writing hypothesis documents", "Only using statistical models"], a: 0, e: "Hypothesis-Driven Development frames product decisions as testable hypotheses and validates them through experiments — reducing risky assumptions." },
    { id: 301, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is product discovery in product management?", o: ["Launching a new product", "Searching for market data", "The process of understanding user problems and identifying valuable feasible solutions before committing to full development", "Finding lost products"], a: 2, e: "Product Discovery deeply understands user problems, explores solutions, and validates ideas before committing to full development — reducing risk of building the wrong product." },
    { id: 302, t: "Product Dev", q: "What does JTBD (Jobs to Be Done) theory focus on?", o: ["Understanding the fundamental job a customer is trying to accomplish — guiding product design around true user needs", "Job posting management", "Tracking team tasks", "Job descriptions for developers"], a: 0, e: "Jobs to Be Done theory focuses on understanding the underlying 'job' customers hire a product to do — guiding design around genuine needs rather than surface preferences." },
    { id: 303, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is customer journey mapping in product development?", o: ["Mapping customers' physical locations", "Road mapping product features", "Tracking customer spending", "Visualizing the complete experience customers have with a product — from initial awareness through purchase and ongoing use"], a: 3, e: "Customer Journey Mapping visualizes the complete customer experience — identifying touchpoints, pain points, and opportunities to improve satisfaction at each stage." },
    { id: 304, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is a pivot in startup and product development?", o: ["A fundamental change in product strategy based on learning from market feedback", "Launching a new marketing campaign", "Rotating a chart", "Pivoting data in a spreadsheet"], a: 0, e: "A Pivot is a fundamental strategic change in product direction — made when market feedback indicates the current approach isn't working and a different strategy is needed." },
    { id: 305, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is product lifecycle management?", o: ["Managing a product from conception through launch and ongoing maintenance to eventual retirement", "Conducting user testing", "Writing software code", "Managing physical product inventory"], a: 0, e: "Product Lifecycle Management involves managing all stages of a product — from conception through development, launch, ongoing improvement, and eventual retirement." },
    { id: 306, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is iterative design in product development?", o: ["Designing the product once and never changing it", "Continuously refining the product based on user feedback and evolving requirements", "Using only one design team", "Designing products sequentially without feedback"], a: 1, e: "Iterative design embraces continuous refinement based on user feedback — repeatedly testing, learning, and improving the product design." },
    { id: 307, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is time-to-market and why does it matter?", o: ["Server response time", "The time from product conception to market availability — shorter time-to-market provides competitive advantage", "Time to deliver physical goods", "The time to train ML models"], a: 1, e: "Time-to-Market is the duration from product concept to market availability — shorter time-to-market enables first-mover advantage and earlier revenue generation." },
    { id: 308, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is ROI in the context of product development decision-making?", o: ["Return on Information", "Return on Investment — the financial return relative to the cost of development", "Risk of Implementation", "Rate of Iteration"], a: 1, e: "ROI (Return on Investment) measures the financial gain from a product relative to its development cost — a key metric for prioritizing product investments." },
    { id: 309, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is product analytics used for?", o: ["Measuring how users interact with the product to understand behaviour, identify issues and guide data-driven product decisions", "Counting product inventory", "Financial accounting", "Server performance monitoring"], a: 0, e: "Product Analytics tracks and analyses user interactions with the product — providing insights that drive data-informed decisions about features, UX improvements, and growth." },
    { id: 310, t: "Product Dev", q: "What is feature prioritization in product management?", o: ["The process of deciding which features to build first based on value, effort and strategic alignment", "Creating feature documentation", "Deleting unused features", "Listing all possible features"], a: 0, e: "Feature Prioritization decides which features to develop first based on factors like user value, development effort, strategic importance, and market timing." }

